source_code.code:
public class PR_41370 {

public static void main (String [] args) {
	Display display = new Display ();
	Shell shell = new Shell (display);
	final Text text = new Text (shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.V_SCROLL | 
SWT.H_SCROLL);
	text.addListener (SWT.Modify, new Listener () {
		public void handleEvent (Event e) {
			System.out.println ("Modify: " + text.getText ());
		}
	});
	text.setText ("Hello");
	text.append (" There!");
	text.pack ();
	shell.pack ();
	shell.open ();
	while (!shell.isDisposed ()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch ()) display.sleep ();
	}
	display.dispose ();
}
}

Bug.WithStack:
The component Text has a fix for updating the controls text 
when in SWT.MULTI-mode. The fix sends a message to the control,
telling it that the text has changed. 
This fix is not included in the append-method.
The work around is not necessary in the append case as the following code 
demonstrates:

import org.eclipse.swt.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.*;

public class PR_41370 {

public static void main (String [] args) {
	Display display = new Display ();
	Shell shell = new Shell (display);
	final Text text = new Text (shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.V_SCROLL | 
SWT.H_SCROLL);
	text.addListener (SWT.Modify, new Listener () {
		public void handleEvent (Event e) {
			System.out.println ("Modify: " + text.getText ());
		}
	});
	text.setText ("Hello");
	text.append (" There!");
	text.pack ();
	shell.pack ();
	shell.open ();
	while (!shell.isDisposed ()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch ()) display.sleep ();
	}
	display.dispose ();
}
}

Intresting, according to the JavaDoc, the type parameter should be
SWT.MULTI. When creating the Text according to :

final Text text = new Text (shell, SWT.BORDER | SWT.MULTI);

the append method does not work properly. 
Then problem is that on Windows, when there is no room for the text to be 
visible, it is not even inserted into the control.  Hence, no SWT.Modify is 
issued.

