Tod, should I disregard the problem mention on comment #1 ?

I've tested both scenarios anyway, case 1 works fine for me.
Case 2 fails cause SWT will only be able to find the active shell after it gets
the focus. It means you will need to run a event loop after openning the shell
(this ensures that the Shell receives the focus in event).

After shell.open() add the line:
while (display.readAndDispatch());

On windows all this happens synchronously (my guess) that is why we don't have
this bug there, GTK on the another hand it all gets defered.

Not sure I can help you here. Is it really important for you to have this fixed ?



Yes - disregard the first test. This is important for us as we cannot get the 
active window easily without this code and the active window is used in many 
places in JFace.
A possible fix for this problem is to call bringToTop with true (force == true)
during Shell.open() if the display has just one shell.

Something like this:

public void open () {
	checkWidget ();
	setVisible (true);
	bringToTop (display.getShells().length == 1); //Hacky line
	if (!restoreFocus ()) {
...


Felipe, there is new API in GTK to get the active shell (in 2.0.6 we had to 
track it using the "hasFocus" field of Shell).  FH to investigate the API to 
see if it gives better results.
The only way to know whether a shell is active is to wait for the focus events
from GTK+, as this is handled by the window manager asynchronously (and it can
deny the request if it likes).  The new API in GTK+ simply tracks focus events,
which is what SWT is already doing.

Closing as WONTFIX.
"the active window is used in many places in JFace".

JFace and the workbench should avoid using getActive*.  Everybody should know
which window they're dealing with to begin with.

